		<h2 id="maincontentlink">AYP Communication with Parents</h2>
        <p>Federal  education law says that all public schools have to meet some basic standards. Minnesota  sets goals for schools to meet each year, called Adequate Yearly Progress  (AYP). You can learn more about school performance and AYP at the following Web  sites:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><u><a href="http://education.state.mn.us/ReportCard2005/index.do" target="_blank">Minnesota Schools' Report Cards &gt;&gt;&gt;</a></u></li>
          <li><u><a href="http://ww3.startribune.com/projects/no_child/" target="_blank">Test Results for Minnesota Schools &gt;&gt;&gt;</a></u></li>
          <li><u><a href="http://education.state.mn.us/MDE/Data/Data_Downloads/Accountability_Data/NCLB_AYP/index.html" target="_blank">Minnesota's AYP Lists &gt;&gt;&gt;</a></u></li>
        </ul>
        <p>Some schools  offer a special program called Title I, which provides extra help for students  who are behind academically or at risk of falling behind. These are called  &ldquo;Title I schools.&rdquo; You can find out if a school has Title I by asking the  principal, or by looking on the school report card, at the link above.</p>
        <p>When a Title I  school does not meet AYP goals, or when a school district as a whole does not  meet AYP goals, parents must be notified. These schools and districts are  called &ldquo;needing improvement.&rdquo; Schools are required to send a letter or email,  post information on their Web site, and use other formats like newspapers or  radio to notify parents. </p>
        <ul>
          <li><u><a href="http://education.state.mn.us/MDE/Accountability_Programs/No_Child_Left_Behind_Programs/School_Performance_AYP/Parent_Notification/index.html" target="_blank">Minnesota  Department of Education: Parent Notification &gt;&gt;&gt; </a></u></li>
        </ul>
        <p>Sometimes, there  are special services, called Supplemental Educational Services (SES, or free  tutoring) and transportation for school choice, which parents can access for  their child when a school or district is &ldquo;needing improvement&rdquo; and that  information can also be in the AYP letter. All schools and districts &ldquo;needing  improvement&rdquo; need parents to be involved in making the school better, and the  letter will give ideas of things parents can do.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><u><a href="http://education.state.mn.us/MDE/Academic_Excellence/School_Choice/Public_School_Choice/Supplemental_Education_Services/index.html" target="_blank">Minnesota  Department of Education: Supplemental Educational Services &gt;&gt;&gt; </a></u></li>
          <li><u><a href="http://education.state.mn.us/MDE/Accountability_Programs/School_Improvement/index.html" target="_blank">Minnesota  Department of Education: School Improvement &gt;&gt;&gt;</a></u></li>
        </ul>
